to an indigenist approach to education. Tanaka recounts how pre-service teachers enrolled in a crosscultural course in British Columbia immersed themselves in indigenous ways of knowing as they worked alongside indigenous wisdom keepers. Transforming cedar bark, buckskin, and wool into a mural that tells stories about the land upon which the course took place, they discovered new ways of learning that support not only intellectual but also tactile, emotional, and spiritual forms of knowledge. By sharing how one group of non-indigenous teachers learned to privilege indigenous ways of knowing in the classroom, Tanaka opens a path for teachers to nurture indigenist crosscultural understanding in their own classrooms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical pedagogyzCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEducationzCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSocial life and customsxStudy and teachingzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEducationzCanada. 0aMulticultural educationzCanada. 0aTeachingzCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh1 aCajete, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311142000440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482953340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774829533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774829533/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-142000-4  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  